@roseveleth Thank you for writing this article. The sound setup and barstool issues happen to me all the time and the solution shouldn't be Dress like a man" https:// motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/ j5a753/design-bias-conference-chairs …"
p.s. I don't think any of this is intentional. It's just rarely taken into consideration, and it should be.

Normal chairs aren't a problem. If you have to perch on top of a bar stool when you didn't expect to, that is. The sound pack issue shouldn't be a surprise by now when there are so many female speakers, but it seems to be every time (it gets clipped to the top of the dress).

I’m a conference organizer and want my speakers to feel good so I’m in favor of wearing the dress that makes them feel confident. But if the dress is too short for when you sit down I’d recommend wearing a slightly longer dress or skirt.

The other thing mentioned is the stage: these are usually (95% of the time?) elevated and it will be VERY difficult for the audience NOT to look up your skirt from where they sit. Bar stools obviously don’t help, but apart from the tables with cloth, what chairs do work?

I honestly don’t think this is intentional or that sound guys (girls?) are to blame. A microphone needs to be clipped onto something. They can’t duct tape it to your back. If you have a dress with a small belt it won’t be an issue.

Dear Conference Organizers: Speakers sometimes wear dresses. Every time I do an event the sound guys react like they have never seen this. Also avoid the basic instinct shot by not making us perch on bar stools. https:// motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/ j5a753/design-bias-conference-chairs …

I have been doing conferences for 10 years and the sound guys always react as if they have never seen a speaker in a dress before. If I'm not wearing trousers (so they can clip the battery pack there) it's a crisis.

text: It really is. We almost accept it as the cost of doing business, and it shouldn't be.
Almost EVERY woman I've asked (granted they're all in tech, media or finance) has had an unwanted work-related harassment experience. Sad indeed.
The truth is most women have had some experience or other like this and that's the really sad thing.

And the stranger who tapped on my ground floor window at midnight when I was 20. In my half asleep state I opened the curtains and he was exposing himself. And the man who followed me around a foreign city for several hours when I was 22. It was scary.

Well.. except for that time a colleague pushed me up against a wall in a bar, aggressively, out of nowhere and definitely unwanted. And the couple of times I was groped in public places -- public transport and a bar -- from behind by men I never identified.

My husband asked me this evening if I had ever been sexually harassed and I said no, thinking he meant in a work situation. Plenty of sexism but no sexual harassment. Which made me feel lucky, which is sad in itself.

It's a practice that predates the Internet by a significant margin. It was just as wrong to call it 'free' then as it is now.
But that's already a given. It's been a given, since, I dunno, since the Internet has been up.
Saying Sign up for our newsletter and get <thing>" is perfectly fine, but it's disingenuous to pretend that's somehow free. You're paying for it with information instead of cash"

3/ I'm exaggerating. I'd use one of my real email (one I use for subscriptions) and use my real name (because signing up for their newsletter does not cost me a thing, and might actually have some value at no extra cost for me.) At some point, we must have a sense of proportion.

2/ They want info. Sure, my name is Inigo Montoya", my address is 1331 Sesame Street, and my e-mail address is " http:// real.email .i.use.for.spam.shits.and.giggles@gmail.com". I get the link from said email registration and voila. Zero cost from me other than using my PC."

1/ Well, at this point we are playing semantics. Of course it isn't free. We need access to the internet (and ergo a computer, internet connection and power) to reach it. By definition, it isn't free (and almost nothing is.) But it is free" in that it doesn't cost me a thing."
and requiring that I sign up for a newsletter to proceed is just icing on the cake
I have lots of email addresses, and it's very easy to just make something up, but asking for information to access something means that it's not free.
